ChatGPT said:

Think of a decorator in Django as a small ‚Äúattachment‚Äù you place on top of a function to give it extra powers without changing the main function code.
In views.py, decorators help you add behavior to your views in a clean, controlled way.

Let me break it down simply.

‚úÖ Why we use decorators in Django views?
1Ô∏è‚É£ To add extra features to a view

For example:

@csrf_exempt ‚Üí disables CSRF protection for that view

@login_required ‚Üí only logged-in users can access

@require_POST ‚Üí only allows POST requests

@permission_required ‚Üí restricts based on permissions

Instead of writing all this logic inside the function, you attach a decorator on top.

‚úÖ Example with and without decorator
Without decorator
def my_view(request):
    if request.method != "POST":
        return HttpResponseNotAllowed()
    if not request.user.is_authenticated:
        return HttpResponse("Login first")
    ...


Too much code inside the function.

With decorator
from django.contrib.auth.decorators import login_required
from django.views.decorators.http import require_POST

@login_required
@require_POST
def my_view(request):
    ...


Cleaner, readable, reusable.

üîí What about csrf_exempt specifically?

Django automatically protects your site from CSRF attacks.
But when you're sending API requests using Postman, React, mobile app, JS fetch, Django will block POST request unless you pass CSRF token.

If you don‚Äôt want CSRF check for a specific view, you use:

from django.views.decorators.csrf import csrf_exempt

@csrf_exempt
def your_api(request):
    ...


‚ö†Ô∏è Only use it for APIs you trust. Don‚Äôt disable CSRF everywhere.

üß† Short explanation to remember

Decorator = extra feature you add to a view without changing the function itself.
It keeps your views clean, safe, and organized.

